  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is due to an assertion
in LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() that validates the agreement between
the legacy cost model (selectVectorizationFactor) and the new VPlan-based cost
model unless the chosen VPlan contains additional simplifications. For the
provided reproducer, the two cost models pick different VFs, but
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() incorrectly returns false, indicating no
extra simplifications, which triggers the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nThe minimized test contains a loop with a branch on invariant condition %c.
In the else path a wide shift \"shl i32 999, %sext\" is computed, where %sext is
(urem 100, %d) << 12. Except for rare divisors of 100, the shift count is >= 32,
making the result poison. The VPlan-based pipeline can simplify or effectively
ignore this instruction (e.g. treating it as invariant/predicated and hoistable),
reducing cost. The legacy cost model still accounts for its per-iteration cost.
Thus BestFactor.Width (chosen by VPlan cost) differs from LegacyVF.Width.\n\n3.
Root Cause Analysis:\nThe assertion fallback relies on
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() to detect when the VPlan has
removed/optimized instructions not reflected in the legacy model. That function
collects all instructions represented by VPlan recipes (SeenInstrs) and then
scans loop instructions, returning true if an instruction is not represented and
not marked to be skipped. It currently uses CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true)
to decide whether to ignore an instruction. skipCostComputation() returns true
for three categories: (a) explicitly precomputed and marked (SkipCostComputation
set), (b) ValuesToIgnore, (c) VecValuesToIgnore. Categories (b)/(c) include
invariant/predicated instructions intentionally ignored in the VPlan cost model,
which ARE simplifications relative to the legacy model. However
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications treats them as non-simplifications by
calling skipCostComputation, thereby suppressing detection of real extra
simplifications. Consequently it returns false and the assertion fires.\nThe wide
shift instruction in the reproducer falls into the
ValuesToIgnore/VecValuesToIgnore category (treated as ignored in VPlan costing),
so planContainsAdditionalSimplifications incorrectly filters it out.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 7324-7331 in LoopVectorize.cpp inside
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications.\nChange the final any_of lambda logic to
only treat instructions explicitly recorded in CostCtx.SkipCostComputation (those
whose costs were already precomputed to match legacy behavior) as
non-simplifications. Do not consult skipCostComputation(), which also hides
invariant/predicated simplifications. This allows the function to return true
when instructions are ignored due to invariance/predication, satisfying the
assertion condition that the VF difference stems from additional
simplifications.\nConcrete change:\nReplace:\nreturn !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&
!CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\nWith:\nbool AlreadyAccounted =
CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.contains(&I);\nreturn !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&
!AlreadyAccounted;\n\nRationale: We narrow the skip logic to only those
instructions deliberately pre-accounted (inductions, exits, reductions, branches)
and treat all other ignored instructions (e.g. invariant/predicated ones removed
by VPlan) as additional simplifications.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy refining
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to correctly classify ignored
invariant/predicated instructions as additional simplifications, the assertion
condition becomes true for this test case (difference in VF attributable to
simplifications). This prevents the crash while preserving the intended
debug-only verification semantics. The functional vectorization decision remains
unchanged; only the debug assertion handling is corrected.",
